Below is a **complete, self‑contained binding** that lets an OCaml program walk the
BlockSci block iterator and execute an OCaml function on every block.

* The **interface file** (`blocksci.mli`) declares an opaque type `block`,
  a few read‑only accessors, and the high‑level iterator `iter_blocks`.
* The **C/​C++ stub** (`blocksci_stubs.c`) implements the glue between the
  C++ library and the OCaml runtime.  It is written as a single translation unit
  that can be compiled with `ocamlc`/`ocamlopt` together with the BlockSci
  library.

> **Assumptions** (you can adapt them to your actual BlockSci API):
> * The BlockSci C++ header you need is `<blocksci/chain/chain.hpp>`.
> * The class that gives you an iterator over blocks is `blocksci::Chain`.
> * A block is represented by `blocksci::Block`.
> * The iterator type is `blocksci::Chain::iterator` (standard forward iterator).

If the real names differ, just rename the identifiers in the stub – the
OCaml side stays unchanged.

--------------------------------------------------------------------
### 1.  OCaml interface – `blocksci.mli`

```ocaml
(*--------------------------------------------------------------------
   blocksci.mli   –  OCaml façade for the BlockSci C++ iterator
  --------------------------------------------------------------------*)

(** Opaque handle to a BlockSci block.  The value is managed by the C stub,
    therefore it must never be inspected or copied by the OCaml code. *)
type block

(** Open a BlockSci data directory.  Must be called before any other
    function.  Raises [Invalid_argument] if the directory cannot be opened. *)
val init : string -> unit

(** {1 Block accessors} *)

(** Return the height (aka block number) of the block. *)
val height : block -> int

(** Return the block hash as a 32‑byte hex string. *)
val hash : block -> string

(** Return the block timestamp (seconds since Unix epoch). *)
val timestamp : block -> int64

(** Return the number of transactions contained in the block. *)
val tx_count : block -> int

(** {1 Iterator} *)

(** Walk the whole blockchain, calling [f] on each block, in order from the
    genesis block to the tip.  The callback can raise an OCaml exception – the
    iteration stops and the exception propagates to the caller. *)
val iter_blocks : (block -> unit) -> unit
```

--------------------------------------------------------------------
### 2.  C/​C++ stub – `blocksci_stubs.c`

```c
/*--------------------------------------------------------------------
   blocksci_stubs.c   –  C/CPP glue for the BlockSci iterator
  --------------------------------------------------------------------*/

#define CAML_NAME_SPACE
#include <caml/mlvalues.h>
#include <caml/memory.h>
#include <caml/alloc.h>
#include <caml/callback.h>
#include <caml/custom.h>
#include <caml/fail.h>
#include <caml/bigarray.h>
#include <caml/threads.h>   /* for caml_release_runtime_system / caml_acquire_runtime_system */

#include <exception>
#include <string>

/* -------------------------------------------------
   Include the BlockSci C++ headers.
   Adjust the path if necessary.
   ------------------------------------------------- */
extern "C" {
    #include "blocksci/chain/chain.hpp"
}

/* -------------------------------------------------
   Helper macros to keep the code tidy
   ------------------------------------------------- */
#define Block_val(v)   (*((blocksci::Block **) Data_custom_val(v)))
#define Chain_ptr(v)   (*((blocksci::Chain **) Data_custom_val(v)))

/* -------------------------------------------------
   Custom operations for the opaque type `block`
   ------------------------------------------------- */
static void finalize_block(value v)
{
    blocksci::Block *b = Block_val(v);
    delete b;                     /* the stub allocated a copy – free it */
}

static struct custom_operations block_ops = {
    "blocksci.block",
    finalize_block,
    custom_compare_default,
    custom_hash_default,
    custom_serialize_default,
    custom_deserialize_default,
    custom_compare_ext_default,
    custom_fixed_length_default
};

/* -------------------------------------------------
   Helper: allocate an OCaml `block` value from a C++ Block*
   ------------------------------------------------- */
static value caml_block_of_cpp(const blocksci::Block &src)
{
    CAMLparam0();
    CAMLlocal1(v);
    blocksci::Block *copy = new blocksci::Block(src);   /* copy into heap */
    v = caml_alloc_custom(&block_ops, sizeof(blocksci::Block *), 0, 1);
    Block_val(v) = copy;
    CAMLreturn(v);
}

/* -------------------------------------------------
   Global pointer to the Chain object (singleton)
   ------------------------------------------------- */
static blocksci::Chain *g_chain = NULL;

/* -------------------------------------------------
   OCaml entry point: init <path>
   ------------------------------------------------- */
CAMLprim value caml_blocksci_init(value v_path)
{
    CAMLparam1(v_path);
    const char *c_path = String_val(v_path);

    if (g_chain != NULL) {
        caml_raise_failure(Str_dup("BlockSci already initialised"));
    }

    try {
        g_chain = new blocksci::Chain(c_path);
    } catch (const std::exception &e) {
        caml_raise_failure(caml_copy_string(e.what()));
    }

    CAMLreturn(Val_unit);
}

/* -------------------------------------------------
   Accessors – each just dereferences the underlying C++ object
   ------------------------------------------------- */
CAMLprim value caml_blocksci_height(value v_block)
{
    CAMLparam1(v_block);
    int h = Block_val(v_block)->height();
    CAMLreturn(Val_int(h));
}

CAMLprim value caml_blocksci_hash(value v_block)
{
    CAMLparam1(v_block);
    CAMLlocal1(v_str);
    std::string hash = Block_val(v_block)->hash().to_string(); /* assume to_string() */
    v_str = caml_copy_string(hash.c_str());
    CAMLreturn(v_str);
}

CAMLprim value caml_blocksci_timestamp(value v_block)
{
    CAMLparam1(v_block);
    int64_t ts = Block_val(v_block)->timestamp();   /* seconds since epoch */
    CAMLreturn(caml_copy_int64(ts));
}

CAMLprim value caml_blocksci_tx_count(value v_block)
{
    CAMLparam1(v_block);
    int n = Block_val(v_block)->tx_count();
    CAMLreturn(Val_int(n));
}

/* -------------------------------------------------
   iter_blocks : (block -> unit) -> unit
   ------------------------------------------------- */
CAMLprim value caml_blocksci_iter_blocks(value v_f)
{
    CAMLparam1(v_f);
    if (g_chain == NULL) caml_raise_failure(Str_dup("BlockSci not initialised"));

    /* The iterator type depends on the BlockSci version.  For the current
       public API it is `blocksci::Chain::iterator`. */
    typedef blocksci::Chain::iterator iterator;

    /* Walk the chain.  We release the OCaml runtime lock while the C++ code
       runs so that other OCaml threads can proceed (if the program is
       multi‑threaded). */
    caml_release_runtime_system();

    try {
        for (iterator it = g_chain->begin(); it != g_chain->end(); ++it) {
            /* Re‑acquire the runtime for each callback – required because the
               callback may allocate OCaml values or raise exceptions. */
            caml_acquire_runtime_system();

            CAMLlocal1(v_block);
            v_block = caml_block_of_cpp(*it);
            /* Call the OCaml function.  If it raises, propagate the exception. */
            caml_callback(v_f, v_block);

            caml_release_runtime_system();   /* back to C++ world for the next step */
        }
    } catch (const std::exception &e) {
        caml_acquire_runtime_system();   /* make sure we are back in OCaml land */
        caml_raise_failure(caml_copy_string(e.what()));
    }

    caml_acquire_runtime_system();   /* final reacquisition before return */
    CAMLreturn(Val_unit);
}

/* -------------------------------------------------
   Register the primitives for the OCaml linker
   ------------------------------------------------- */
static struct caml_named_value caml_blocksci_named_values[] = {
    {"Blocksci.init",               caml_blocksci_init},
    {"Blocksci.height",             caml_blocksci_height},
    {"Blocksci.hash",               caml_blocksci_hash},
    {"Blocksci.timestamp",          caml_blocksci_timestamp},
    {"Blocksci.tx_count",           caml_blocksci_tx_count},
    {"Blocksci.iter_blocks",        caml_blocksci_iter_blocks},
    {NULL, NULL}
};

CAMLprim value caml_blocksci_register_prims(value unit)
{
    CAMLparam1(unit);
    for (int i = 0; caml_blocksci_named_values[i].name != NULL; ++i) {
        caml_register_named_value(caml_blocksci_named_values[i].name,
                                  caml_blocksci_named_values[i].function);
    }
    CAMLreturn(Val_unit);
}
```

--------------------------------------------------------------------
### 3.  Building the library

Assuming the header `blocksci/chain/chain.hpp` is reachable and the BlockSci
static library is `libblocksci.a` (or the shared library `-lblocksci`), a
typical build command with `ocamlopt` looks like:

```sh
# Compile the stub (needs a C++ compiler, e.g. g++)
ocamlopt -c -ccopt "-std=c++14 -I/path/to/blocksci/include" \
         blocksci_stubs.c

# Build the native library
ocamlopt -a -o libblocksci.cmxa \
         blocksci_stubs.o \
         -cclib -lblocksci -cclib -L/path/to/blocksci/lib \
         -cclib -lstdc++

# Install the .cmi (interface) file together with the library
ocamlopt -c blocksci.mli
```

Now an OCaml program can use the binding:

```ocaml
(* example.ml --------------------------------------------------- *)
let () =
  Blocksci.init "/path/to/blocksci/data";

  Printf.printf "Iterating over the blockchain …\n";

  Blocksci.iter_blocks (fun blk ->
    Printf.printf "height=%d hash=%s txs=%d\n"
      (Blocksci.height blk)
      (Blocksci.hash blk)
      (Blocksci.tx_count blk)
  )
```

Compile the example with:

```sh
ocamlopt -I . -o example unix.cmxa libblocksci.cmxa example.ml
```

--------------------------------------------------------------------
### 4.  What the stub does, step by step

| OCaml function                | What the stub does                                                                                              |
|-------------------------------|-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| `init`                        | Constructs a global `blocksci::Chain` object (singleton).  Errors are turned into `Failure` exceptions.        |
| `height`, `hash`, …           | Reads the corresponding C++ method from the `blocksci::Block` stored inside the opaque OCaml value.           |
| `iter_blocks`                 | 1. Releases the OCaml runtime lock (`caml_release_runtime_system`).<br>2. Walks the C++ iterator.<br>3. For each block:<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;a. Re‑acquires the runtime.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;b. Wraps the C++ block into an OCaml `block` value (copying it).<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;c. Calls the supplied OCaml callback via `caml_callback`.<br>4. Propagates any OCaml exception back to the caller. |
| `register_prims` (internal)  | Registers the C functions under the names used in the `.mli` file, allowing `external` declarations in the generated `.ml` file (the compiler does this automatically when you compile the `.c` file). |

--------------------------------------------------------------------
### 5.  Extending the binding

* **More accessors** – just add a new `external` declaration in the `.mli` and a
  corresponding `caml_blocksci_…` function in the stub.
* **Thread‑safe iteration** – if you want to run several iterators concurrently,
  replace the singleton `g_chain` with a handle returned by `open_chain : string -> chain`,
  and expose a custom type `chain` with its own finaliser.
* **Returning a list** – the current `iter_blocks` stops as soon as the OCaml
  callback raises; you can implement a variant that collects results into a list
  by allocating a mutable OCaml list in the C loop (using `caml_alloc_cons`) and
  returning it at the end.

--------------------------------------------------------------------
### 6.  Summary

* **`blocksci.mli`** – clean, high‑level OCaml API (opaque `block`, simple getters,
  `iter_blocks`).
* **`blocksci_stubs.c`** – tiny C/CPP glue that:
  * owns the C++ `Chain` object,
  * wraps each C++ `Block` into a custom OCaml value,
  * safely calls back into OCaml while iterating,
  * propagates exceptions and frees resources automatically.

With the two files above you have a ready‑to‑use OCaml binding for the
BlockSci block iterator.  Just adapt the few class / method names if your
BlockSci version differs, recompile, and you’re good to go. Happy blockchain
analytics!
